<font color="#FF0000">DISCRIMINATION</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan  2 13:51:15 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
For many years, something has been troubling me about the treatment of Americans of African descent who served in Vietnam.  Because of discrimination against veterans in my profession, I have been working outside of the United States since 1974, but I have been attempting to combat the discrimination by filing complaints and suing employers who discriminate against me as a veteran.  Of course, I have tried to collect as many statistics as I can on employment practices.<br>
   During the 1980s, I collected some employment statistics from the Department of Labor showing the placement rates of the state and territorial employment services, which are given large amounts of Federal funds for setting up programs to promote employment among veterans.  The statistics showed that veterans were not getting a fair break, but they also showed that there were considerable regional differences.  The Department of Labor uses the so-called 4/5 test to determine whether there is statistical evidence of discrimination.  According to this test, if the members of a group have less than 4/5, or 80%, as much chance of being hired than the members of the most successful group, then a prima facie case is established for discrimination, and the employer or agency involved should be obligated to provide a plausible reason for the lower percentage.  The Department of Labor is supposed to enforce the equal opportunity provisions of the law, but it does not apply this test for Vietnam Era veterans.  My statistics showed that Vietnam Era veterans had less than 80% as much chance as anyone else of being placed in a job by a state or territorial employment agency in 10 states, the District of Columbia, and the Virgin Islands.  NB: This was 80% as much chance as anyone else and not the most successful group, by the way.<br>
   The worst percentages were evident for the District of Columbia and the Virgin Islands, where, in 1986, a veteran seeking employment had only about 50% and 30% as much chance as anyone else, respectively, of being placed in a job. The population of both of these two territories consists overwhelmingly of Americans of African descent.  In the case of the District of Columbia, it is also noteworthy that the main employer is the U. S. Federal Government and contractors doing business directly with it.<br>
   During my service in Vietnam, I observed that a large number of combat troops were of African descent, and statistics that I later found have indicated that they constituted a percentage about double their percentage in the general American population.  Because of their willingness to risk their lives to serve their country, I have always believed that they deserved a better break than they are presently getting in America.  However, it seems to me that those persons who did come forward to serve are being discriminated against to a degree even worse than veterans of other ancestry within their own group.  It seems that the only thing on the employment market less desirable than a Vietnam War veteran is a Vietnam Veteran of African descent.<br>
   Because the statistics were not broken down according to race in the various states, I cannot say whether this employment pattern is general or only applies to D.C., where the Federal Government is the main source of employment.  However, I have never seen any comment on this or any studies that address this issue.  Apparently, any gains that have been made among Americans of African descent are not being shared by the Vietnam War veterans among them.<br>
   I can add one more point.  The employment I have had outside of the United States includes research and teaching at a Brazilian university and at a Brazilian research institute. I have spent the better part of five years in Brazil.  After living and working with Brazilians, and Europeans for that matter, it is difficult to adjust myself to the American society during my rare visits to the United States. There really is a polarization of the races in the United States, which may be less evident to an American who has not observed other societies to see that things can be different.<br><br>

